'''Braj Basi Lal''' (born 2 May 1921<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ignca.nic.in/invitations/invite_20170719.pdf | format=PDF |title=Invitation to the fifth chapter of Sanskriti Samvaad Shrinkhla |publisher=Indira Gandhi National Centre for the Arts |date=19 July 2017 |access-date=30 April 2018 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>), better known as '''B. B. Lal''', is an [[India]]n [[archaeologist]]. He was the Director General of the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] (ASI) from 1968 to 1972 and has served as Director of the [[Indian Institute of Advanced Study|Indian Institute of Advanced Studies, Shimla]]. Lal also served on various [[UNESCO]] committees.<ref name="BBLalChair">[http://www.iitk.ac.in/drpg/chair/bblchair.htm B. B. Lal Chair at IIT Kanpur] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320054512/http://www.iitk.ac.in/drpg/chair/bblchair.htm |date=20 March 2012 }}, Indian Institute of Technology, Kanpur website.</ref>

He received the [[Padma Bhushan]] Award by the [[Government of India]] in 2000.<ref name="BBLalChair"/>

==Early life and background==
Born in [[Jhansi]], United Provinces of Agra and Oudh, India,<ref name="ConinghamYoung2015">{{cite book|last1=Coningham|first1=Robin|last2=Young|first2=Ruth|title=The Archaeology of South Asia: From the Indus to Asoka, c.6500 BCE–200 CE|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hB5TCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA83|accessdate=30 April 2018|date=31 August 2015|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521846974|page=83 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Lal obtained his master's degree in [[Sanskrit]], including the [[Vedas]], with a First class degree from [[Allahabad University]], India.<ref name="19thCenturyParadigms">[http://www.archaeologyonline.net/indology/2007/19th%20Century%20Paradimgs.pdf 'Let not the 19th century paradigms continue to haunt us!'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504165157/http://www.archaeologyonline.net/indology/2007/19th%20Century%20Paradimgs.pdf |date=4 May 2012 }}, Inaugural Address delivered at the 19th International Conference on South Asian Archaeology at University of Bologna, Ravenna, Italy on 2–6 July 2007, [http://www.archaeologyonline.net/artifacts/19th-century-paradigms.html online link], archaeologyonline.net</ref><ref name=today>{{cite web | title = Archaeologist B.B. Lal talks about his book 'The Saraswati Flows On' : Books |publisher= India Today|url = http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/archaeologist-b.b.-lal-talks-about-his-book-the-saraswati-flows-on/1/231683.html|date=12 November 2001| accessdate = 9 August 2013  }}</ref>

==Career==
After his studies, Lal developed interest in archaeology and in 1943, became a trainee in excavation under a veteran British archaeologist, [[Mortimer Wheeler]], starting with [[Taxila]],<ref name=today/> and later at sites such as [[Harappa]] and [[Sisupalgarh]] in [[Odisha]].<ref name=bookReview/> Lal went on to work as an archaeologist for more than fifty years.

In 1968, he was appointed the Director General of the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] where he would remain until 1972. Thereafter, Lal served as Director of the [[Indian Institute of Advanced Study|Indian Institute of Advanced Studies, Shimla]].<ref name="BBLalChair"/>

==Archaeological work==
The [[Archaeological Survey of India]] had performed conservation and restoration of [[Buddhas of Bamiyan]], Khwaj Parsa’s Mosque at [[Balkh]] and [[Khwaja Abu Nasr Parsa shrine|the shrine of Khwaja Abu Naser]] under R. Sen Gupta and Lal in [[Afghanistan]].<ref name=ASI2>[http://asi.nic.in/asi_abroad.asp Archaeological endeavours abroad], [[Archaeological Survey of India]] Official website.</ref>

Between 1950-52, Lal worked on the archaeology of sites accounted for in the Hindu epic ''[[Mahabharata]]'', including [[Hastinapura]], the capital city of [[the Kurus]]. He made discoveries of many [[Painted Grey Ware culture|Painted Grey Ware (PGW) sites]] in the [[Indo-Gangetic Plain|Indo‑Gangetic Divide]] and upper [[Yamuna]]‑[[Ganga]] [[doab]].<ref name=bookReview>[http://ifihhome.tripod.com/bookreviews/sarasvatiflowsonrv.html Book review by Dr. V. N. Misra], Book review of The Saraswati Flows on: the Continuity of Indian Culture, by Chairman of Indian Society for Prehistoric and Quaternary Studies journal Man and Environment; (vol. XXVI, No. 2, July–December 2001)</ref>

In [[Nubia]], the [[Archaeological Survey of India]], Lal and his team discovered [[Middle stone age|Middle]] and [[Late Stone Age]] tools in the terraces of the river [[Nile]] near Afyeh. The team excavated a few sites at Afyeh and cemetery of C-group people, where 109 graves would be located.<ref name=ASI2/><ref name=Egypt>{{cite journal| pmc=3385173 | pmid=22754242 | doi=10.4103/0971-6866.96686 | volume=18 | title=A comparison of Fulani and Nadar HLA | journal=Indian J Hum Genet | pages=137–8 | author=Winters C}}</ref> Lal worked on [[Mesolithic]] site of Birbhanpur (West Bengal), [[Chalcolithic]] site of [[Gilund]] (Rajasthan) and [[Indus Valley Civilization|Harappan]] site of [[Kalibangan]] (Rajasthan).

In 1975-76, Lal worked on the "Archaeology of Ramayana Sites" project funded by the ASI, which excavated five sites mentioned in the Hindu epic ''[[Ramayana]]'' - [[Ayodhya]], Bharadwaj ''[[ashram]]'', [[Nandigram]], [[Chitrakoot district|Chitrakoot]] and [[Shringverpur|Shringaverapur]]. In the seven-page preliminary report submitted to the Archaeological Survey of India (ASI), Lal disclosed the discovery by his team of "pillar bases", immediately south of the [[Babri mosque]] structure in Ayodhya.<ref name=bookReview/><ref>{{cite web | title = I found pillar bases back in mid-seventies: Prof Lal | url =http://www.indianexpress.com/oldStory/19644/|publisher=Indian Express | accessdate = 9 August 2013 }}</ref>

Prof. B. B. Lal has published several books and over 150 research papers and articles in national and international scientific journals.<ref name="BBLalChair"/><ref name=bookReview/> In his 2002 book, ''The Saraswati Flows On'', Lal criticised the earlier [[Indo-Aryan migration|Aryan invasion/migration theory]], arguing that the [[Rig Veda|Rig Vedic]] description of the [[Sarasvati River]] (which dried up by 2000 BCE) as "overflowing" contradicts the claim made by certain previous historians that the Indo-Aryan migration occurred 300 years after they contend the Sarasvati River dried up (in 1500 BCE) and which they also contended had led to the end of the [[Indus Valley Civilization]].<ref name=today/>

== Ayodhya dispute ==
In Lal's 2008 book, ''Rāma, His Historicity, Mandir and Setu: Evidence of Literature, Archaeology and Other Sciences'', he writes (that): 
<blockquote>
"Attached to the piers of the Babri Masjid, there were twelve stone pillars, which carried not only typical Hindu motifs and mouldings, but also figures of Hindu deities. It was self-evident that these pillars were not an integral part of the Masjid, but were foreign to it."<ref>{{cite web | title = Ayodhya: High Court relies on ASI's 2003 report|publisher=Economic Times | url = http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-01/news/27573745_1_hindu-temple-b-b-lal-asi|date=Oct 1, 2010| accessdate = 9 August 2013 }}</ref>
</blockquote>

==Legacy==
The B. B. Lal Chair at [[Indian Institute of Technology, Kanpur]] ([[IIT, Kanpur]]) has been established in his honour.<ref>{{cite web | title = Faculty Chairs | publisher = IIT Kanpur | url = http://www.iitk.ac.in/drpg/facultychair.htm | accessdate = 9 August 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140218220149/http://www.iitk.ac.in/drpg/facultychair.htm | archive-date = 18 February 2014 | dead-url = yes | df = dmy-all }}</ref>

The British archaeologists [[Stuart Piggott]] and D.H. Gordon describe ''Copper Hoards of the Gangetic Basin'' and the ''Hastinapura Excavation Report'', two of Lal's works published in the ''Journal of the Archaeological Survey of India'', as ''models of research and excavation reporting''.<ref name=bookReview/>

