[[Image:Francisco de Ibarra.jpg|thumb|Francisco de Ibarra]]
'''Francisco de Ibarra''' (1539 &ndash;June 3, 1575) was a [[Basque people|Basque]] [[explorer]], founder of the city of [[Durango, Durango|Durango]], and [[governor]] of the Spanish province of [[Nueva Vizcaya, New Spain|Nueva Vizcaya]], in present-day [[Durango]] and [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]].
==Biography== Francisco de Ibarra was born about 1534 in [[Eibar]], [[Gipuzkoa]], in the [[Basque Country (historical territory)|Basque Country]] of [[Spain]]. He went to [[Mexico]] as a young man, and upon the recommendation and financing of his uncle, [[conquistador]] and wealthy mine owner [[Diego de Ibarra]], Francisco was placed at the head of an expedition to explore northwest from [[Zacatecas, Zacatecas|Zacatecas]] in 1554. The young Ibarra noted silver in the vicinity of present-day [[Fresnillo]], but passed it by. He explored further and founded towns at San Martín and Avino, where the silver mines made him a mine owner in his own right.<ref>P. J. Bakewell (1971) ''Silver Mining and Society in Colonial Zacatecas 1546–1700'', Cambridge: University Press, p. 28–29.</ref> Ibarra's expedition to Zacatecas was later documented by Spanish historian [[Baltasar Obregón]], who traveled with Ibarra in 1554.
In 1562, Ibarra headed another expedition to push farther into northwest Mexico. In particular, he was searching for the fabled golden city of Copala (also called [[Seven Cities of Gold|Cibola]]). He did not find the mythical treasure, but explored and conquered what is now the Mexican state of [[Durango (state)|Durango]]. Ibarra was appointed governor of the newly formed province of Nueva Vizcaya (New Biscay) in 1562, and the following year he founded the city of [[Durango, Durango|Durango]] to be its capital.<ref name="Bannon_1970_Borderlands">{{cite book |title=The Spanish Borderlands Frontier, 1513-1821 |author=[[John Francis Bannon]]|location=Albuquerque |publisher=Holt, Rinehart, and Winston |year=1970 |edition=1 |isbn=0030851696 |OCLC=5685684 |pages=308 |series=Histories of the American frontier}}</ref>{{rp|29,53-4}}
In 1564, Ibarra, following rumors of rich mineral deposits, crossed the [[Sierra Madre Occidental]] to conquer what is now southern [[Sinaloa]]. Prospectors discovered silver veins in the new territory, and in 1565, de Ibarra founded the towns of [[Copala, Sinaloa|Copala]] and [[:es:Pánuco (Sinaloa)]].
Soldiers under Ibarra's direction explored north from [[Durango]] in 1567, and founded the town of [[Santa Bárbara, Chihuahua|Santa Bárbara]] in present-day [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]] to mine the silver they found there.
Francisco de Ibarra died on 3 June 1575 in [[Pánuco, Sinaloa]], one of the silver-mining cities that he founded.<ref>José Ignacio Gallegos (1960) ''Durango Colonial, 1563–1821'', Mexico City: Editorial Jus, p. 78.</ref>
